51st Avenue (foreground), north side, between 21st Street and 11th Street, viewing northeastward toward the 49th Avenue viaduct over the Long Island Railroad tracks. This area was later made part of a new highway system feeding the Queens-Midtown Tunnel. The tall building is the Queens Borough Hall on 21st Street; the Queensboro Terminal garage is on 50th Avenue.

November 21, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue (foreground), north side, between 21st Street and 11th Street. The view is northeastward across empty lots, near the Long Island Railroad tracks, toward the 49th Street viaduct. This area was later made part of the approach to the Queens Midtown Tunnel, involving extensive engineering changes. On the left is the Queens Borough Hall, on 21st Street.

November 21, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue (foreground), north side, between 21st Street and 11th Street. The view is northeastward across the Long Island Railroad tracks. Across this area was later constructed a new highway to connect the Queens-Midtown Tunnel with the distant parts of Queens. On the left is the Queens Borough Hall, at 21st Street and 49th Avenue; on the right is a Sheffield Farms Company building. The elevated highway in the background is 49th Avenue.

November 21, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue, west from near 21st Street. This area later became part of a new broad highway leading to the Queens-Midtown Tunnel entrance at Vernon Avenue.

November 18, 1938

New York City Tunnel Authority

51st Avenue, west from near 21st Street. This part of the avenue and the broad clearance on the right were later made part of the new broad highway leading to the Queens-Midtown Tunnel.
